---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import TableOfContents from '../../components/ui/TableOfContents';
import MethodologyCard from '../../components/ui/MethodologyCard.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between SFX and ATX power supplies?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The primary difference is size. ATX is the standard desktop form factor (150mm x 86mm x 140mm+), whereas SFX is designed for small form factor cases (125mm x 63.5mm x 100mm). SFX units use smaller fans (usually 80-92mm) and shorter cables."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I install an SFX PSU in an ATX case?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, but you will need an SFX-to-ATX adapter bracket. Many premium SFX power supplies include this bracket in the box. You may also need cable extensions since SFX power cables are significantly shorter than standard ATX cables."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="SFX vs ATX PSU: Form Factors & Mounting Guide — PSUCheck"
  description="Learn the differences between SFX and ATX power supplies. Explore dimensions, brackets, cable lengths, and cooling configurations for SFF builds."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <a href="/methodology" class="badge badge-safe" style="text-decoration:none;">✓ Sizing Methodology Verified</a>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>SFX vs ATX PSU: Small Form Factor vs Desktop Standard</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          Choosing between an SFX and ATX power supply depends entirely on your PC chassis volume.
          This guide outlines the differences in sizing, noise levels, and installation constraints.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>Dimensions Comparison</h2>
          <p>
            The physical volume comparison between these two standards is substantial:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>ATX (Advanced Technology eXtended):</strong> 150 mm width × 86 mm height × 140 mm (to 200 mm) depth.</li>
            <li><strong>SFX (Small Form Factor):</strong> 125 mm width × 63.5 height × 100 mm depth.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            SFX power supplies are roughly half the volume of a standard ATX unit, freeing up critical
            space for airflow and routing in Mini-ITX cases (such as the Lian Li A4-H2O or Fractal Ridge).
          </p>

          <h2>Cable Length & Mounting Templates</h2>
          <p>
            Because SFX units are destined for tight spaces, their modular cables are typically
            300mm to 400mm long, compared to 600mm+ on standard ATX power supplies.
          </p>
          <div class="important-warning">
            <strong>⚠ Cabling Tip:</strong> If you install an SFX unit in a Mid-Tower ATX case, the 24-pin
            motherboard cable or 8-pin EPS CPU cable may not reach their respective sockets. You will need
            sleeved extension cables in this scenario.
          </div>

          <h2>Cooling and Fan Profile</h2>
          <p>
            ATX power supplies can accommodate 120mm to 140mm fans, which move large volumes of air
            at low RPMs, keeping operation silent. SFX units are limited to 80mm or 92mm fans, which must
            spin faster (generating a higher-pitched sound profile) to maintain safe thermal limits.
          </p>

          <div style="margin-top:3rem;">
            <a href="/psu-calculator" class="btn btn-primary">Check your build clearances</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <TableOfContents client:load />
          <MethodologyCard />
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Calculators</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pc-builder">🖥️ PC Build Cost Calculator</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Related Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/sfx-l-psu-guide">SFX-L PSU Compatibility</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-sizing-guide">PSU Sizing Guide</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
.guide-article { padding: 4rem 0; }
.guide-header { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.guide-meta { display:flex; gap: 1rem; align-items:center; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
.guide-lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-secondary); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
.guide-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .guide-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 8fr) minmax(0, 4fr); }
}
.guide-content h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content p, .guide-content li { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
.important-warning { background: var(--color-surface-raised); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent-orange); padding: 1rem; border-radius: var(--radius-md); margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
.guide-sidebar { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
</style>
